{{Infobox civil servant |name = B. B. Ashok Kumar |native_name = |image = |birth_name = Biddanda Bopanna Ashok |birth_place = |birth_date = |death_place = |order = |office = [[Karnataka Police|Karnataka Police Service]], [[Government of Karnataka]] |term_start = 1977 |term_end = 31 July 2012 |predecessor = |successor = |office1 = |term_start1 = |term_end1 = |predecessor1 = |successor1 = |nationality = [[India]]n |alma_mater = |occupation = Civil servant |father = |mother = |spouse = |children = |website = }}
'''B. B. Ashok Kumar''' (also known as '''Tiger Ashok Kumar''') is a retired [[Assistant Commissioner of Police (India)|Assistant Commissioner of Police]] credited with arresting several notorious criminals and the many police encounters in which he was involved trying to capture [[Habitual offender|hardened criminals]].<ref name=b>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.bangalorefirst.in/?p=2376 |title=‘Tiger Ashok Kumar’ retires |publisher=Bangalorefirst.in |date=2012-08-04 |accessdate=2015-03-12}}</ref>
==Early life== Born in bavali village, parane post[[Virajpet]], [[Kodagu district]] of [[Karnataka]] state, he is the son of a coffee estate manager in [[Koppa, India|Koppa-Chikkamagalur]].
==Police service== Kumar joined the [[Karnataka Police|Karnataka State Police Service]] in 1977 and is credited with 18 encounters. While being a part of Special Task Force of [[Karnataka Police]] tasked to nab forest brigand [[Veerappan]], Ashok is reported to have slain 13 accomplices of the brigand.<ref name=b />
Ashok and his police team were in the news for the Kammanahalli encounter killing of [[history-sheeter]] Station Shekar.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tamil Nadu |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/When-Bangalore-was-rid-of-an-underworld-don/article14758168.ece |title=When Bangalore was rid of an underworld don - TAMIL NADU |publisher=The Hindu |date= |accessdate=2018-03-27}}</ref>
Kumar retired from service on 31 July 2012<ref name=b /> and faces constant threat to his life from the criminal underworld.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/bangalore/report-retired-banglore-police-officer-faces-life-threat-1796884 |title=Retired Banglore police officer faces life threat |publisher=Dnaindia.com |date=2013-02-06 |accessdate=2018-03-27}}</ref>
==Honours and awards== He won the [[Police Medal (India)|President of India's Gold Medal]] three times and the gold medal of the Chief Minister of Karnataka once. Ashok was given the nickname of 'Tiger' by the Home Minister in 1984.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}
{| class="wikitable sortable" |- ! Year !! Name of Award or Honour |- |1986 |President of India Gallantry Gold Medal |- |1998 |President of India Meritorious Service Gold Medal |- |2006 |President of India Distinguished Service Gold Medal |- |1992 |Chief Minister of Karnataka Gold Medal |- |2011 |Karnataka Govt Kempegowda Award |}
==In films and literature== There are five Kannada movies made on his experience and adventures to date. *''Amaanusha (1989)'', with [[Ananth Nag]] acting as Kumar *''Circle Inspector'' (1995), with [[Devaraj]] acting as Kumar *''[[Deadly Soma]]'' (1998), with Devaraj as Kumar *''[[Deadly-2]]'' (2004), with Devaraj as Kumar *''Mynaa'' (2013) with [[Sharath Kumar]] acting as Kumar
Kumar has authored two books, * ''Huliya Nenapugalu'' - {{ISBN|8128025856}} * ''Bullet Savari'' - {{ISBN|9788128025860}}
