{{BLP sources|date=May 2010}} {{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians --> | name = James Floyd Soileau | image = | caption = Floyd Soileau at Floyd's Record Shop, 1967 | image_size = | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1938|11|2}} | birth_place = Ville Platte, Louisiana | death_date = | death_place = | instrument = | genre = [[Cajun music|Cajun]], [[country music|country]], [[swamp blues]], [[swamp pop]], [[zydeco]] | occupation = [[Record producer]] | years_active = 1950s-Today | label = Big Mamou, Vee-Pee, Swallow, Jin, [[Maison de Soul]], Kom-a-day, Flat Town Music Company | associated_acts = | website = http://www.flattownmusic.com/Floyds-Record-Shop-C523.aspx }}
'''James Floyd Soileau''' (born November 2, 1938) is an [[Americans|American]] [[record producer]].
==Biography== Soileau was born in Faubourg, a small community between [[Ville Platte, Louisiana|Ville Platte]] and [[Washington, Louisiana|Washington]], [[Louisiana]]. He grew up speaking [[Cajun French]] and did not speak English until attending school at the age of 6 years.<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p126811|pure_url=yes}}|title=Biography: Floyd Soileau|last=Harris |first=Craig|publisher=[[All Media Guide|AMG]]|accessdate=9 May 2010}}</ref> In his junior year of high school, he did an afternoon [[Cajun]] music show as a part-time job with [[KVPI (AM)|KVPI]] radio in Ville Platte. After graduating from Ville Platte High in 1956, he opened a small [[Gramophone record|record]] store, [[Floyd's Record Shop]] and discovered that although people were still interested in them, [[Cajun French]] records were no longer being produced. With the financial help of a friend, [[Ed Manuel]] (a [[juke box]] operator from [[Mamou, Louisiana]]), who wanted new French records for his juke boxes, Floyd released his first record on the Big Mamou label by artists [[Austin Pitre]] and [[Milton Molitor]]. In 1957 [[Lawrence Walker]] and [[Aldus Roger]] helped Floyd launch his own label, Swallow Records.
Over the past 40 years, Swallow Records has released 265 [[single (music)|45rpm single records]] and 151 [[album]]s of Cajun French music, including recordings by [[Adam Hebert]], [[Belton Richard]], [[The Balfa Brothers|Dewey Balfa and the Balfa Brothers]], [[Nathan Abshire]], [[Jambalaya Cajun Band]], [[Paul Daigle & Cajun Gold]], [[D.L. Menard]], and many more, plus recordings by the Cajun French story teller, [[Marion Marcotte]]. 1958 saw the beginning of [[Jin Records]] with artists such as [[Clint West]], [[Tommy McLain]] & [[the Boogie Kings]], [[Camille Bob|Lil' Bob & The Lollipops]], [[Warren Storm]], [[Skip Stewart]], [[Rockin' Sidney]], [[Rod Bernard]], Johnny Allan and others making significant contributions to what was the, then, controversial [[swamp pop]] music. In 1975 he established his [[Maison de Soul]] record label, devoted to [[Creole music|Creole]] and [[Zydeco]] music, including artists such as [[Clifton Chenier]], [[Rockin' Dopsie]], [[Keith Frank]], [[Chris Ardoin]], [[Zydeco Force]], [[Jeffery Brousard]], and others. He has always encouraged his artists to compose new songs to record, and his Flat Town Music Company now publishes over 2800 songs, a majority of which are Cajun, swamp pop, and zydeco songs.
His Swallow Publications has published two books on the Cajun French language, ''Cajun Dictionary'' and ''Cajun Self-taught'', both by [[Rev. Jules Daigle]], and Jeff Hannusch's ''I Hear You Knockin''', the story of early [[New Orleans rhythm and blues]]. He operated Swallow Recording Studios in Ville Platte for over 15 years, and sold his last studio in 1975 to Ronnie Kole, who moved the studio to [[Slidell, Louisiana]]. That year he opened a vinyl record pressing plant and printing company for [[LP record]] jackets and labels, the only such facility in Louisiana. The plant closed in 1994. Eventually, the store would close but the online mail order business still continues.
In 1959, he married his high school sweetheart Jinver Ortego. They have three daughters, Catherine, Connie and Cindy, and one son, Christopher. Floyd was inducted into the Acadian Museum in Louisiana on October 19, 2002.<ref name="museum">{{cite web|url=http://www.acadianmuseum.com/legends.php?viewID=139|title=Living Legends. Floyd Soileau. |accessdate=2014-08-18}}</ref>
