'''Geoffrey Paul "Geoff" Regan''' {{post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|MP}} (born 22 November 1959) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician, member of parliament for [[Halifax West]] and the current [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons]]. Under [[Paul Martin]], he was [[Minister of Fisheries and Oceans (Canada)|Minister of Fisheries and Oceans]] from 2003 to 2006.

==Early life and career==
Regan was born in [[Windsor, Nova Scotia]]. Regan is the son of [[Gerald Regan]], a former [[Premier of Nova Scotia]] and Cabinet Minister under [[Pierre Trudeau]], and Carole Harrison, the daughter of [[John Harrison (Canadian politician)|John Harrison]], a Member of Parliament from Saskatchewan.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title = Meet Geoff Regan, the new Speaker of the House of Commons|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/speaker-house-geoff-regan-liberal-mp-1.3349744|website = www.cbc.ca|accessdate = 2015-12-04}}</ref> Two of his sisters  are also well-known: [[Nancy Regan]] was a well-known local television personality with [[CTV Atlantic|ATV]], [[Laura Regan]] is an [[actress]].{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}

Regan graduated from [[Sackville High School]] in 1977 and then earned his Bachelor of Arts in Political Science from [[St. Francis Xavier University]] in 1980. Following university, Regan went on to earn a law degree from [[Dalhousie University]], graduating in 1983. He was admitted to the Nova Scotia Barristers’ Society in 1984 and practiced real estate and commercial law before entering public life.

Regan was a member of Toastmasters for almost ten years, in the late 1980s to early 1990s.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Meet Geoff Regan, Canada's Speaker of the House of Commons|journal=The Toastmaster|issue=August 2016|pages=16–19|url=https://www.toastmasters.org/~/media/26219FAE47504B18854118DA4D0FD80E.ashx|accessdate=2 September 2016}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

==Federal politics==
Regan was first elected to the House of Commons as part of the Liberal landslide victory in the [[Canadian federal election, 1993|1993 federal election]] under [[Jean Chrétien]].<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald.ns.ca/fedelect97/archive/931026108.html|title=Atlantic region hands Liberals near-clean sweep|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=October 26, 1993|accessdate=2015-08-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011121074131/http://www.herald.ns.ca/fedelect97/archive/931026108.html|archivedate=November 21, 2001 }}</ref> He was defeated in the [[Canadian federal election, 1997|1997 election]] by [[New Democratic Party|NDP]] candidate [[Gordon Earle]], mainly because of the federal government's changes to employment insurance.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald.ns.ca/fedelect/97archive/jun3/970603153.html|title=NDP's Earle becomes first Black MP for N.S.|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=June 3, 1997|accessdate=2015-08-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010522114533/http://www.herald.ns.ca/fedelect/97archive/jun3/970603153.html|archivedate=May 22, 2001}}</ref>

After regaining his seat in the [[Canadian federal election, 2000|2000 federal election]], Regan was appointed [[Parliamentary Secretary]] to the [[Leader of the Government in the House of Commons]], a position then held by [[Don Boudria]].<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald.ns.ca/cgi-bin/home/displaypackstory?2000/11/28+236.raw+FE00Nov28+2|title=Halifax West's Regan 'delighted' to be back|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=November 28, 2000|accessdate=2015-08-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050124091442/http://www.herald.ns.ca/cgi-bin/home/displaypackstory?2000%2F11%2F28+236.raw+FE00Nov28+2|archivedate=January 24, 2005|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> In 2003, Paul Martin appointed him as [[Minister of Fisheries and Oceans (Canada)|Minister of Fisheries and Oceans]].<ref name=":0" />

Regan was the Regional Minister for Nova Scotia in the newly formed government of [[Paul Martin]], sworn in on December 12, 2003. Regan was re-elected in the [[Canadian federal election, 2004|2004 federal election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.herald.ns.ca/cgi-bin/home/displaypackstory?2004/06/29+279.raw+FE04Jun29+2|title=Geoff Regan: 'What a thrill'|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=June 29, 2004|accessdate=2015-08-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050906115355/http://www.herald.ns.ca/cgi-bin/home/displaypackstory?2004%2F06%2F29+279.raw+FE04Jun29+2|archivedate=September 6, 2005|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> He would keep position in cabinet in Martin’s minority government. In February 2004, Regan was appointed to act as [[Minister of Justice (Canada)|Minister of Justice]] and [[Attorney General of Canada]], in matters related to [[Maher Arar]].

=== In opposition ===
[[File:Michael Ignatieff at the Halifax Ferry Terminal.jpg|thumb|left|Regan with Liberal leader [[Michael Ignatieff]] during the [[Canadian federal election, 2011|2011 federal election]] campaign]]

Upon the defeat of the Liberal government in the [[Canadian federal election, 2006|2006 election]], he was appointed by [[Bill Graham (Canadian politician)|Bill Graham]], Interim Leader of the Official Opposition, to the shadow cabinet as the Official Opposition Critic for Human Resources and Skills Development. During his time as critic, Regan introduced a private members’ bill to expand Canada Access Grants for disabled and low income students. In January 2007, he was appointed to the newly created Liberal Priorities and Planning Committee, which was chaired by then Liberal Opposition Leader [[Stéphane Dion]]. In March 2008, Regan was named Chair of the Caucus Committee on Environmental Sustainability. Regan also served as Vice-Chair of the House of Commons Standing Committee on Environment and Sustainable Development.

Regan was re-elected in [[Canadian federal election, 2008|2008]], and [[Canadian federal election, 2011|2011 federal elections]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/regan-holds-halifax-west-for-liberals-1.1002100|title=Regan holds Halifax West for Liberals|publisher=CBC News|date=May 3, 2011|accessdate=2015-08-17}}</ref> despite significant Liberal losses in both. Regan won his seat by a few percentage points in the latter election as the Liberals finished in third place.<ref name=":0" /> Under the leadership of [[Stephane Dion]], Regan served as Opposition Critic for Human Resources and Skills Development. Under [[Michael Ignatieff]], Regan served as Liberal Critic for Natural Resources, and later, Public Works and Government Services and also as the Liberal Natural Resources Critic under leader [[Justin Trudeau]] and the  Vice-Chair of the [[Standing Committee on Natural Resources]].

=== Speaker of the House of Commons ===
[[File:Geoff Regan MP.jpg|thumb|Regan in 2008.]]

Regan was re-elected in the [[Canadian federal election, 2015|2015 federal election]] with 68% of the vote as the Liberal party swept all 32 [[Atlantic Canada]] seats and formed a majority government.<ref name=":0" /> On December 2, 2015, Regan was selected as [[Speaker of the House of Commons (Canada)|Speaker of the House of Commons]] in secret ballot by members of the [[42nd Canadian Parliament|42nd Parliament]] over Liberal candidates [[Denis Paradis]], [[Yasmin Ratansi]] and Conservative [[Bruce Stanton]].<ref name=":0" /> Regan won on the first ballot and is the first speaker from Atlantic Canada in over a hundred years.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Geoff Regan elected House Speaker as 42nd Parliament opens|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/parliament-opens-speaker-election-1.3348640|website = www.cbc.ca|accessdate = 2015-12-04}}</ref>

== Awards and honours ==
* Metro Food Bank Society Community Leadership Award (1992)
* Halifax Board of Trade Certificate of Merit (1992)
* Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal (2002)
* Appointed member of the Queens’s Privy Council for Canada (2003)
* Elisabeth Mann Borgese Medal (2005) The International Ocean Institute awarded Regan then Minister of Fisheries and Oceans for his "exemplary leadership in the field of Ocean Governance."
* Lebanese Community Recognition Award (2008)
* Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal (2012)

== Personal life ==
Regan's wife, [[Kelly Regan]], is a provincial [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]] and [[Nova Scotia Liberal Party|Liberal]] cabinet minister in Nova Scotia.<ref name=":0" />

