'''Mary V. Riley''' (December 24, 1908 – October 5, 1987) was an [[Apache]] tribal council member who was instrumental in the economic development of the [[White Mountain Apache]] Tribe. She was the first woman to be elected to serve on the tribal council and worked toward bringing timber and tourism industries to the reservation to ensure their economic stability. She was inducted into the [[Arizona Women's Hall of Fame]] posthumously in 1988.

==Early life==
Mary Velasquez was born on December 24, 1908{{#tag:ref|The 1916 Indian Census gives her birth date as December 20, 1908.{{sfn|U.S. Indian Census|1916|p=339}} (Note, this family reference on various census reports is R-24).{{sfn|U.S. Indian Census|1909|p=151}}|group="Notes"}} at Fort Apache, on the [[Fort Apache Indian Reservation|White Mountain Apache Reservation]]{{sfn|Arizona Women's Hall of Fame|1988}} to Nalatzalay (Belle née Ivins) and Jesus Velasquez.{{sfn|U.S. Indian Census|1909|p=151}}{{sfn|Arizona Women's Hall of Fame|1988}}{{sfn|Arizona Death Records|October 1, 1943}} Her father was born in [[Fort Davis, Texas]] to Mexican nationals from [[Coahuila]], Martín and Juana (née Rivers) Velasquez,{{sfn|Arizona Death Records|October 24, 1943}} and came to Fort Apache traveling with soldiers from Ft. Davis, as a child with his mother. He worked for a time as a translator and scout{{sfn|Richens|1977}}{{sfn|Cavanaugh|1960|p=1}} and then managed a ranch where he provided supplies to the soldiers at the fort.{{sfn|Arizona Women's Hall of Fame|1988}} Her mother was a full-blood Apache and the daughter of Nadischaay.{{sfn|U.S. Indian Census|1909|p=151}} Velasquez and her siblings grew up on their father's farm, helping with farm chores. She attended three years of school, but was forced to leave in the [[1918 flu pandemic]] to help with sick relatives.{{sfn|Arizona Women's Hall of Fame|1988}}

Though she was unable to return to school, Velasquez became fluent in three languages: [[Apache language|Apache]], Spanish, and English. She read newspapers widely.{{sfn|Arizona Women's Hall of Fame|1988}}{{sfn|Adley-SantaMaria|1999|p=16}} Velasquez first married Kurt Johnson{{sfn|''The White Mountain Independent''|2012}} and then around 1936,{{sfn|White|1986|p=10}} married Peter Kessay Riley,{{sfn|''The Arizona Republic''|1987|p=53}}{{sfn|''The Arizona Republic''|1990|p=11}} with whom she raised her five children, all of whom were also trilingual, and to whom she stressed the importance of gaining an education.{{sfn|Arizona Women's Hall of Fame|1988}}{{sfn|Adley-SantaMaria|1999|p=16}} She farmed as her father had, raising corn, potatoes, pumpkin and squash, as well as turkey, goat and sheep.{{sfn|White|1986|p=10}}

==Tribal career==
In 1958, Riley became the first woman elected to serve on the White Mountain Apache Tribal Council.{{sfn|Arizona Women's Hall of Fame|1988}} She served on the health, education and welfare committee of the tribe and at various times, chaired the committee.{{sfn|''The Arizona Republic''|1960|p=15}}{{sfn|''The Arizona Republic''|1963|p=8}} She made numerous trips to both the state capital, [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] and federal capital in [[Washington, D. C.]], lobbying on behalf of the tribe.{{sfn|Cavanaugh|1960|p=1}}{{sfn|''The Arizona Republic''|1985|p=256}} In an effort to improve situations for tribal members, she evaluated many programs for both economic and socio-cultural gains, looking at federal programs such as [[Job Corps]]{{sfn|MacEarian|1965|p=40}} the [[Boy Scouts of America]],{{sfn|''The Arizona Daily Sun''|1959|p=8}} and [[Bureau of Indian Affairs]] loan programs for economic development. Riley represented three districts of the reservation{{sfn|Rolland|1972|p=26}} and was instrumental in projects, such as the Alchesay-Williams Creek National Fish Hatchery Complex, the Fort Apache Timber Company (FATCO), and the [[Sunrise Park Resort|Sunrise Park Ski Resort and Hotel]], among others, to expand the tribal enterprises and provide economic stability for the tribe.{{sfn|White|1986|p=10}}{{sfn|McDowell|1967|p=132}}{{sfn|Rolland|1972|p=26}}

Ground was broken for FATCO in 1962 and by 1963 had replaced the hiring of outside operators to manage the timber reserves of the tribe. By managing their own lumber harvests and operating three saw mills, the tribe was able to provide both jobs for tribal members and goods to sell to a wider clientele.{{sfn|Sheridan|Parezo|1996|p=89}}{{sfn|Cavanaugh|1962|p=12}} Around the same time, the Alchesay-Williams Hatchery was developed to stock the local lakes which had been created on the reservation and protect species listed as [[Threatened species|threatened]] or [[Endangered species|endangered]]. Employment opportunities for tribal members were increased through jobs at the hatchery, related jobs in the tourism sector, and additional revenues were garnered through the sale of fishing licenses.{{sfn|Behnke|2010|p=129}} One of the largest projects was to convert 1.6 million acres of their lands into the Sunrise Park Resort. Constructing 20 recreational lakes, campsites, fishing and hunting venues, a ski resort, and hotels, the Tribal Council utilized their lands to generate a year-round tourist industry.{{sfn|Rolland|1972|p=26}}{{sfn|McDowell|1967|p=132}}

Riley was interviewed as part of an [[Oral history preservation|Oral History Project]] sponsored by the Arizona State Department of Libraries and Archives in 1977.{{sfn|Richens|1977|p=1-2}} After twenty years on the council, Riley retired in 1978.{{sfn|''The Arizona Republic''|1985|p=256}} She was honored by the state in 1984 during the Statehood Day Celebrations for her leadership and development.{{sfn|''The Arizona Daily Star''|1984|p=14}} Profits from FATCO were used to build the Mary V. Riley Building, which houses the tribal educational department.{{sfn|Sheridan|Parezo|1996|p=89}}

==Death and legacy==
Riley died on October 5, 1987 at White Mountain River Indian Hospital in [[Whiteriver, Arizona]].{{sfn|''The Arizona Republic''|1987|p=53}} Posthumously, she was inducted into the [[Arizona Women's Hall of Fame]], in 1988.{{sfn|Conner|1988|p=43}}

