'''Pandelela Rinong [[Malaysian names#Names of members of other groups|Anak]] Pamg''', {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of the Defender of the Realm|AMN]] [[Order of the Star of Hornbill Sarawak|JBK]]}} (born 2 March 1993) is a Malaysian [[diving (sport)|diver]] specialises in the 10-metre platform event. She is a two-time [[Summer Olympics|Olympic]] medalist and has won a total of four medals at the [[World Aquatics Championships|World Championships]].

Pandelela represented Malaysia at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] where she finished 27th in [[Diving at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Women's 10 metre platform|10m platform]]. She won the gold medal at the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]]. She was chosen to be the flagbearer of Malaysia at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]]. She went on to win the bronze medal in the [[Diving at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Women's 10 metre platform|10m platform]], becoming the first Malaysian female athlete to win an [[Olympic medal]], as well as the first in any sport other than badminton. At the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], she won the silver medal in the [[Diving at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Women's synchronized 10 metre platform|10m synchronized platform]] with [[Cheong Jun Hoong]].<ref>{{cite news |title=(Olympic) Divers Cheong Jun Hoong and Pandelela Rinong win silver, first medal for Malaysia in Rio 2016 |author=Vijesh Rai |url=http://www.nst.com.my/news/2016/08/164366/olympic-divers-cheong-jun-hoong-and-pandelela-rinong-win-silver-first-medal |publisher='' [[New Straits Times]]'' |date=10 August 2016 |accessdate=10 August 2016}}</ref>

==Early and personal life==
Pandelela was born in (Kampung) Kupuo Jugan, a Bidayuh village in [[Bau, Sarawak|Bau]], Sarawak to Hartini Lamin and Pamg Joheng.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2012/07/21/pandelela-shining-example-of-true-grit/ |title=Pandelela – Shining example of true grit |publisher=[[The Borneo Post]] |date=21 July 2012 |accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref><ref name="hopefulforgold">{{cite web |author1=Jonathan Edward |author2= |lastauthoramp=yes |url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/dad-hopeful-of-gold-soon-for-pandelela |title=Dad hopeful of gold soon for Pandelela |publisher=[[Malay Mail]] |date=11 August 2016 |accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref><ref name="2012londonwin">{{cite web |author1=Anasathia Jenis |author2= |lastauthoramp=yes |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2012/08/11/pamg-over-the-moon-with-daughters-victory/ |title=Pamg over the moon with daughter’s victory |publisher=[[The Borneo Post]] |date=11 August 2012 |accessdate=26 May 2017}}</ref> She is of [[Bidayuh]] ethnicity, a [[Bumiputera (Malaysia)|Bumiputera]] native to the Malaysian state of [[Sarawak]]. She is the second of four siblings.<ref name="hopefulforgold"/> At the age of seven she was selected as a state diver and continued her training at the [[Bukit Jalil Sports School]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Dennis Wong |author2=Desmond Davidson |lastauthoramp=yes |url=http://www.nst.com.my/nation/general/pandelela-does-nation-proud-with-medal-win-1.123655/ |title=Pandelela does nation proud with medal win |publisher=[[New Straits Times]] |date=11 August 2012 |accessdate=20 August 2012}}</ref> She graduated from [[University of Malaya]] in 2018, majoring in Sports Management Science.<ref name="brightyoungthings">{{cite news |author1=Dian Pasquinal Kaur |author2= |author3= |title=Bright Young Things: National diver Pandelela Rinong on the road to Rio |newspaper=Asia Tatler |date=29 July 2016 |url=http://my.asiatatler.com/society/bright-young-things-national-diver-pandelela-rinong-on-the-road-to-rio }}</ref><ref name="graduate2018">{{cite news |author1=Bernama |author2= |author3= |title=Pandelela to graduate from University Malaya on Tuesday |newspaper=The Borneo Post |date=20 October 2018|url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/10/21/pandelela-to-graduate-from-university-malaya-on-tuesday/ }}</ref>

Pandelela speaks [[Mandarin Chinese]] as well as her [[Land Dayak languages|Bidayuh]] mother tongue, [[Malaysian language|Bahasa Malaysia]] and [[English language|English]]. <ref name="chin2018">{{cite news |author1=Christina Chin|author2= |author3= |title=Pandelela Rinong: Not your average student |newspaper=The Star |date=21 October 2018 |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/education/2018/10/21/pandelela-rinong-not-your-average-student/ }}</ref>

==Career==
Pandelela made her international competition debut in 2007 at the Asian Junior Aquatics Championships where she won four gold medals. At the [[2007 Southeast Asian Games]] in Thailand, she won the gold medal in 10m synchronized platform with Cheong Jun Hoong.

Pandelela made her Olympic debut at the [[2008 Beijing Olympics]] as a 15 year old. She finished 27th in the [[Diving at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Women's 10 metre platform|10 m platform]]. At the [[2009 World Aquatics Championships]], she finished fifth in the [[Diving at the 2009 World Aquatics Championships – Women's 10 metre platform|10 m platform]]. She went on to win the bronze medal in the [[Diving at the 2009 World Aquatics Championships – Women's synchronized 10 metre platform|10 m synchronized platform]] with [[Leong Mun Yee]] where it was also the first-ever diving medal for Malaysia at the World Championships.

Pandelela won two gold medal at the [[2009 Southeast Asian Games]] in Vientiane. She was the flag bearer for the [[Malaysia at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics|Malaysian contingent]] at the [[2010 Summer Youth Olympics]] in [[Singapore]] where she won the silver medals in the 10 m platform event and 3 m springboard event.

At the [[2010 Commonwealth Games]] in New Delhi, she won Malaysia's first ever [[Commonwealth Games]] gold medal in an aquatic sport by winning the 10 m platform event. At the [[2010 Asian Games]] in Guangzhou, she won the bronze medal in 10 m platform and the silver medal in 10m synchronized platform with Leong Mun Yee.

Pandelela was chosen to be the [[2012 Summer Olympics national flag bearers|flag bearer]] of Malaysia at the [[2012 Summer Olympics Parade of Nations]] where she is first national female athlete to be accorded the honour. She competed in the individual 10 m platform, [[Diving at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Women's synchronized 3 metre springboard|3m synchronized springboard]] with Cheong Jun Hoong and the [[Diving at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Women's synchronized 10 metre platform|10 m synchronised platform]] event with Leong Mun Yee.<ref name=first>{{cite web |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2012/08/10/blazing-the-trail/ |author=Zulhilmi Supaat |title=Pandelela, Malaysia’s first woman to win Olympic medal |publisher=[[The Borneo Post]] |date=10 August 2012}}</ref>

She became the first [[Malaysia at the 2012 Summer Olympics|Malaysian]] female athlete to win an Olympics medal, and the first Malaysian athlete to win an Olympics medal in a sport besides badminton by winning a bronze medal in the [[Diving at the 2012 Summer Olympics – Women's 10 metre platform|10 m platform]] at the 2012 Summer Olympics in London.<ref name=first /> To commemorate her success, she was presented with the Johan Bintang Kenyalang (Companion of the Order of the Star of Hornbill) by the Sarawak State Government, in a special investiture ceremony held at the Astana shortly after her triumphant return to her homeland.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sarawak confers award on diver Pandelela |author=Dennis Wong |url=http://www.nst.com.my/nation/general/sarawak-confers-award-on-diver-pandelela-1.127901 |publisher=''[[New Straits Times]]'' |date=22 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> She became Sarawak's first athlete to be accorded with the award.<ref name="JBK2012">{{cite journal |title=Pandelela receives Johan Bintang Kenyalang award |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/community/2012/08/22/pandelela-receives-johan-bintang-kenyalang-award/ |work=[[The Star (Malaysia)]] |accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>

At the [[2013 World Aquatics Championships]] in Barcelona, Pandelela and Mun Yee clinch the bronze medal in 10m synchronized platform with 331.14 points. She also finished sixth in individual 10m platform event. At the [[2013 Southeast Asian Games]] in Naypyidaw, she retained her gold medal in 10m platform event.

Pandelela competed at the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]] in Glasgow. Despite a knee injury, she won the bronze medal in 10m synchronized platform with [[Nur Dhabitah Sabri]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/2015/09/commonwealth-games-surprise-bronze-pandelela|title=COMMONWEALTH GAMES: Surprise bronze for Pandelela|author=Vijesh Rai|date=30 July 2014|publisher=[[New Straits Times]]|accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> She also bagged a silver in the 10m platform with a score of 368.55 points. At the [[2014 Asian Games]] in Incheon, she won the bronze medal in 10 m synchro platform with Leong Mun Yee.

In July 2015, Pandelela made history when she became the first Malaysian to finish on the podium in an individual event at the [[2015 World Aquatics Championships|World Aquatics Championships]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Historic win for Pandelela in World Aquatics Championships |author=Ajitpal Singh |url=http://www.nst.com.my/node/94038 |publisher=''[[New Straits Times]]'' |date=31 July 2015 |accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> She clinched a bronze medal in the individual 10 m platform in Kazan and qualify for the [[2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio de Janeiro Olympics]] in Brazil.<ref>{{cite news |title=Najib congratulates Pandelela for becoming first Malaysian athlete to qualify for Rio Olympics |author=Bernama |url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/sports/article/najib-congratulates-pandelela-for-becoming-first-malaysian-athlete-to-quali |publisher=''[[Malay Mail]]'' |date=31 July 2015 |accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref>

At the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in Rio de Janeiro, she won the silver medal in the [[Diving at the 2016 Summer Olympics – Women's synchronized 10 metre platform|10 m synchronized platform]] with Cheong Jun Hoong, becoming the first Malaysian women's team to win a silver medal at the Olympics.<ref name=NBC-2016-08-09>{{cite episode |series=Rio Olympics |date=9 August 2016 |network=NBC |title=Olympics Primetime}}</ref> In honour of her achievement at the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], The Sarawak Aquatic Centre in [[Petra Jaya]], [[Sarawak]] was officially named Pandelela Rinong Aquatic Centre.<ref name=fmt-aquaticcentre>{{cite news |title=Sarawak Aquatic Centre named after Pandelela Rinong |author=Bernama |url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2016/09/03/sarawak-aquatic-centre-named-after-pandelela-rinong/ |publisher=''[[Free Malaysia Today]]'' |date=3 September 2016 |accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref> After [[2016 Summer Olympics]], Pandelela took a break to recuperate from back and shoulder injuries.<ref name=pandelelaincontrol>{{cite news |author1=Ajitpal Singh|title=Pandelela in control |newspaper=New Straits Times |date=5 February 2017|url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/2017/02/209743/pandelela-control}}</ref>

At the [[2017 World Aquatics Championships]] in Budapest, she won the bronze medal in 10 m synchronized platform with Cheong Jun Hoong. She finished ninth in the individual 10m platform which was won by her partner, Jun Hoong. At the [[2017 Southeast Asian Games]] in Kuala Lumpur, she won the gold medal in newly introduced team event with Gabriel Gilbert Daim.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nst.com.my/sports/others/2017/08/272933/kl2017-malaysia-sweep-diving-gold |title=KL2017: Malaysia sweep diving gold |last=Singh |first=Jugjet |date=26 August 2017 |publisher=[[New Straits Times]] |accessdate=2 September 2017}}</ref> She also retained her gold medal in the individual 10m platform event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nst.com.my/sports/others/2017/08/273870/kl2017-pandelela-retains-gold-individual-10m-platform |title=KL2017: Pandelela retains gold in individual 10m platform |last=Singh |first=Jugjet |date=28 August 2017 |publisher=[[New Straits Times]] |accessdate=2 September 2017}}</ref>

