{{infobox person/Wikidata | fetchwikidata=ALL | onlysourced=yes}}

'''Philomène Belliveau''' (1854 &ndash; 1940) was a Canadian artist of [[Acadian]] descent.

The daughter of Modeste Cormier and Joseph Belliveau, she was born in [[Memramcook]] and was educated at the convent of the Sisters of Sacré Cœur (known as Reed's Castle) in [[Saint John, New Brunswick|Saint John]]. In 1889, she travelled to [[Boston]], where she took courses in painting and drawing. After she returned to New Brunswick, her portraits in [[pastel]] became very popular. The Acadian museum at the [[Université de Moncton]] has four of these portraits in their collection.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.museevirtuel.ca/edu/ViewLoitDa.do;jsessionid=1CB244C5398A9C15054F5B0D455AA1EB?method=preview&lang=EN&id=5102 |title=Philomène Belliveau |work=Art and Culture |publisher=Canadian Heritage Information Network}}</ref><ref name=scvm/>

In 1904, she married judge Alphonse Pierre Garon. The couple settled in [[Shediac]], later moving to [[Rimouski]].<ref name=scvm/>

She died in Rimouski at the age of 85.<ref name=scvm>{{cite web |url=http://culturememramcook.ca/index.php/fr/artistes/peintres/8-philomene-belliveau |title=Philomène Belliveau |publisher=Société Culturelle de la Vallée de Memramcook |language=fr}}</ref>

