'''Preciado Bakish''' ([[Hebrew]]: פרסיאדו בקיש )<ref group="notes">[[Bulgar]]: Пресиадо Бакиш. His surname is sometimes spelled Bakich or Baquiche (http://skachate.ru/jurnalistika/63296/index.html?page=12). The first name is sometimes written "Presiado". The first name Yakir ([[Hebrew]]: יקיר) is sometimes attributed to him. This name could match "expensive", "precious" which would mark a relationship with the Hebrew root Y.K.R. (yakar) and would be a translation of the [[Judaeo-Spanish|Ladino]] name Preciado (or Presiado). See: http://www.sephardicstudies.org/pdf/prom_bulg_jews.pdf ; Arditti, Benjamin (Ed. 1969), Volume I, pp. 20-32. Second first name : Yits'hak (http://skachate.ru/jurnalistika/63296/index.html?page=12).</ref> was a rabbi and a Bulgar member of the Zionist Movement.
==Biographical elements== Born in 1828 at [[Sofia]] ([[Bulgaria]]) to a [[Sephardic Jewish]] family.<ref>On its Sephardic family, see: Hillel Bakis (1992), p. 4.</ref> He died in [[Jerusalem]] at the age of 82 (1910). He was named Chief Rabbi of [[Bulgaria]] (1885–1889; 1895–1898<ref>Arditti Benjamin (1969), Vol. 1, p.: 20-32. See also n° 108 in Anon (2002).</ref> or 1900)<ref>According to Ivanka Gezenko, he served as until 1900</ref> and [[Av Beit Din]] (Chairman of the Rabbinical Court)<ref>http://skachate.ru/jurnalistika/63296/index.html?page=12 (page on Bulgar Jewish Union in Israel).</ref> He participated in the [[First Zionist Congress]]<ref>Z. Loker, "The Sephardic Jews in Bulgaria", in H. Mechoulan (ed. 1992), ''Les Juifs d'Espagne histoire d'une diaspora. 1492-1992', p. 260. However, some sources do not mention its participation (http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/vjw/bulgaria.html)</ref> held on 29, 30 and 31 August 1897 to [[Basel]] (Switzerland) along with three other delegates from Bulgaria (Zvi Belkovsky,<ref>(1865-1948). From Russian citizenship, he was Lecturer at Sofia University.</ref> Karl Herbst, Yehoshua Kalef) and some 200 other members from around the world. These activities have created difficulties and Rabbi Preciado Bakish was not maintained in his functions as Chief Rabbi of Bulgaria after 1900.<ref>Ivanka Gezenko (2014, 2015)</ref> A photograph of Rabbi Bakish was published on a genealogy website<ref>https://www.geni.com/people/%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B1%D0%B8-%D0%9F%D1%80%D0%B5%D1%81%D0%B8%D0%B0%D0%B4%D0%BE-%D0%98%D1%86%D1%85%D0%B0%D0%BA-%D0%91%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%88/4977820646350132340 (2014)</ref>
